-- German Next-Day Power Gains as Wind Production Forecast to Drop
-- B y   L a r s   P a u l s s o n
-- 2011-02-07T09:08:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-07/german-next-day-power-gains-as-wind-production-forecast-to-drop.html
German power for next-day delivery
advanced as production from wind was forecast to drop in
Europe’s biggest market.  Output from  wind turbines , a less predictable source of
energy than nuclear, coal or gas-fired generation, will decline
tomorrow to above 10,000 megawatts from more than 13,000
megawatts today,  Markedskraft Deutschland GmbH  said in an e-
mailed report. That’s still more than the average for this time
of year of 6,000 megawatts. Wind produced 6.8 percent of  Germany ’s power in 2009.  Baseload day-ahead electricity traded at 49.90 euros
($67.78) a megawatt-hour in the over-the-counter market at 9:51
a.m. Berlin time, according to broker data compiled by
Bloomberg. That compares with a price for today of 42.03 euros
as settled in an auction on the  Epex Spot SE  exchange in Paris
yesterday. Baseload is delivered around the clock.  Power for next-year delivery fell for a second day. The
European benchmark dropped 0.4 percent to 52.35 euros a
megawatt-hour, according to broker prices compiled by Bloomberg.
The country,  Europe ’s biggest economy, also gets power from
nuclear, hard coal, lignite, natural gas and solar stations.  Bloomberg tracks prices from brokers including ICAP Plc,
GFI Group Inc., Spectron Group Ltd. and Tullett Prebon Plc.  To contact the reporter on this story:
